A geologic feature is a type of thing and something that exclusively belongs to the geosphere realm. It is alternatively labeled as both a Geologic Feature and a Geological Feature. The definition of a geologic feature is a conceptual entity hypothesized to coherently exist on Earth as a result of geological processes. Examples of individual geologic features include the Lake Eyre Basin, Sarmatian Craton, Victoria Point Sandbar, and Mount Erebus Volcano, with subclasses comprising Basins, Cratons, Shields, Provinces, and Sub-Provinces. The scope of geologic features encompasses sedimentary basins, stratigraphic units, non-stratigraphic (lithodemic) units, stratigraphic event features, provinces, tectonic and structural features, georesource accumulations, and geologically significant sites, among others.
